NOTES_NUMBERS_9_12 = {
    9: {
        12: 'PASSOVER LAMB -- NO BROKEN BONE: \'Nor break a bone of it\' -- this detail is repeated from Exodus 12:46. CHRIST: John 19:33-36 explicitly connects this to Christ\'s crucifixion: the soldiers broke the legs of the two criminals but not of Jesus, \'that the Scripture might be fulfilled: "Not a bone of Him shall be broken."\'  Jesus is the Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7) whose bones remain unbroken.',
        14: 'ONE LAW: The alien (ger) may observe the Passover under the same statute as the native-born. God\'s covenant meal is open to the foreigner who joins himself to YHWH. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Gentile inclusion in the covenant meal foreshadows the Lord\'s Supper, which is open to all who come by faith in Christ.',
        15: 'THE CLOUD AND FIRE: The visible glory of God (Shekinah) rests on the tabernacle -- cloud by day, fire by night. This is the pillar that led Israel from Egypt (Exod 13:21-22), now settled on the completed sanctuary. The cloud is the visible manifestation of YHWH\'s presence. When it moves, they move; when it stays, they stay. Total dependence on divine guidance.',
        22: 'RADICAL OBEDIENCE: Whether two days or a month or a year -- the Israelites wait. This passage repeats \'at the command of the LORD\' five times in nine verses. The emphasis is unmistakable: every movement of Israel\'s life is governed by the immediate, visible direction of God. There is no human itinerary, no five-year plan -- only following the cloud.',
    },
    10: {
        9: 'TRUMPETS IN WARFARE: When Israel blows the trumpets in battle, God remembers them. The trumpet sound does not merely rally troops; it invokes the divine warrior. The word \'remembered\' (nizkartem) means God brings them before His active attention for salvation. ESCHATOLOGY: The last trumpet (1 Cor 15:52; 1 Thess 4:16; Rev 11:15) echoes these silver trumpets -- God remembers His people and comes to save.',
        11: 'DEPARTURE FROM SINAI: Israel has been at Sinai since Exodus 19 -- approximately eleven months. At Sinai they received the law, built the tabernacle, and were organized into a holy army. Now they march toward the Promised Land. Everything between Exodus 19 and Numbers 10:11 is \'at Sinai.\' This verse marks the transition from receiving to marching.',
        33: 'THE ARK LEADS: The ark of the covenant goes three days ahead to find a resting place. YHWH\'s throne scouts the path. God goes before His people into unknown territory.',
        35: 'THE ARK PRAYER: This ancient war cry -- \'Rise up, O LORD!\' (qumah YHWH) -- is one of the oldest liturgical formulas in the Bible. It appears in Psalm 68:1 and Psalm 132:8. When the ark moved, it was YHWH going to war. When it rested, it was YHWH enthroning Himself among His people. The \'myriad thousands of Israel\' (rivevot alfei Yisrael) describe both the human army and, possibly, the heavenly host that accompanies YHWH into battle.',
    },
    11: {
        1: 'THE DESCENT BEGINS: Immediately after leaving Sinai -- within three days (10:33) -- Israel begins to complain. The pattern of the book is now set: God provides, Israel complains, God judges, Moses intercedes. The fire that consumes the camp\'s outskirts is the first of many wilderness judgments.',
        4: 'THE RABBLE: \'The rabble\' (ha\'asaphsuph) -- literally \'the gathered ones,\' probably the mixed multitude of non-Israelites who left Egypt with Israel (Exod 12:38). The infection of discontent spreads from the margins to the center: the rabble craves, then \'the sons of Israel wept again.\' Spiritual corruption often enters through the periphery.',
        5: 'EGYPT NOSTALGIA: \'We remember the fish which we ate free in Egypt\' -- the word \'free\' (chinnam) is staggering. They were slaves. The fish was not free; it was slave rations. Memory distorted by craving romanticizes bondage. This is the spiritual pattern of those who prefer the comforts of slavery to the demands of freedom.',
        15: 'MOSES AT THE BREAKING POINT: \'Please kill me at once\' -- Moses\' despair is raw and honest before God. Compare Elijah (1 Kings 19:4) and Jonah (4:3). The greatest leaders in Scripture reach moments of total exhaustion. God does not rebuke Moses for honesty; He provides help (the seventy elders).',
        17: 'THE SPIRIT ON THE SEVENTY: God takes \'of the Spirit who is upon\' Moses and distributes Him. The Spirit is not divided or diminished; He is extended. This is the model for shared leadership in God\'s economy -- the Spirit who empowers one can empower many. CHRIST: At Pentecost (Acts 2), the Spirit is poured out not on seventy but on all believers, fulfilling Moses\' wish in v.29.',
        25: 'PROPHESYING: The seventy prophesy when the Spirit rests on them -- an ecstatic, visible manifestation confirming their appointment. \'But they did not do it again\' -- the prophesying was a one-time sign of commissioning, not an ongoing gift. The Spirit\'s empowerment continues; the sign does not.',
        29: 'MOSES\' GREAT WISH: \'Would that all the LORD\'s people were prophets!\' -- Moses envisions a day when every Israelite would have the Spirit. Joel 2:28-29 prophesies exactly this. Peter quotes Joel at Pentecost (Acts 2:16-18): \'I will pour out My Spirit on all flesh.\' Moses\' impossible wish becomes Christ\'s accomplished reality.',
        33: 'JUDGMENT ON CRAVING: The quail comes as both provision and judgment. God gives them what they demanded, and it kills them. Psalm 106:15: \'He gave them their request, but sent a wasting disease among them.\' KIBROTH-HATTAAVAH means \'graves of craving\' -- the place where desire consumed those who craved. The lesson: getting what you want apart from what God wants is a curse, not a blessing.',
    },
    12: {
        1: 'MIRIAM AND AARON\'S CHALLENGE: The ostensible complaint is about Moses\' Cushite wife; the real issue is authority (v.2). Miriam is named first, suggesting she instigated. The Cushite woman may be Zipporah (if Cushan = Midian, cf. Hab 3:7) or a second wife. The text does not elaborate because the wife is not the point -- the challenge to Moses\' unique authority is the point.',
        3: 'HUMBLE: \'The man Moses was very humble\' (anav me\'od) -- this parenthetical is often challenged as self-praise if Moses wrote it. But \'humble\' (anav) in Hebrew does not mean \'self-deprecating\'; it means \'lowly, afflicted, dependent on God.\' Moses does not defend himself; God does. That is the mark of true humility.',
        7: 'FAITHFUL IN ALL MY HOUSEHOLD: God\'s defense of Moses uses the language of a trusted steward over the divine household (bayit). Hebrews 3:2-6 quotes this verse and applies it to Christ: \'Moses was faithful in all His house as a servant, but Christ as a Son over His house.\' Christ is greater than Moses because He is the owner, not the servant.',
        8: 'MOUTH TO MOUTH: God speaks to other prophets through visions and dreams (mediated revelation). He speaks to Moses \'mouth to mouth\' (peh el peh) -- directly, clearly, without riddles. \'He beholds the form of the LORD\' (temunah) -- Moses sees YHWH\'s visible manifestation, not His essence (cf. Exod 33:18-23). This unique access is what Miriam and Aaron challenged.',
        13: 'MOSES\' INTERCESSION: Five Hebrew words -- \'El na refa na lah\' -- \'O God, please heal her, please.\' The shortest, most passionate prayer in the Torah. Moses prays for the sister who challenged him. No bitterness, no vindication -- only mercy. CHRIST: \'Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing\' (Luke 23:34).',
        14: 'SEVEN DAYS\' SHAME: God compares Miriam\'s punishment to a father spitting in his daughter\'s face -- a sign of extreme disgrace (Deut 25:9). The seven-day isolation is both judgment and mercy: full public humiliation, but limited in duration. The entire nation waits for Miriam -- no one moves until she is restored.',
    },
}
